  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 5.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "O ye simple, understand wisdom.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " \"The simple,\" those not yet perverted, but easily influenced for good or evil. See on Proverbs 1:4, where also is explained the word ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "ormah",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", used here for \"wisdom;\" equivalent to ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "calliditas",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " in a good sense, or ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "πανουργία",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", as sometimes employed in the Septuagint; so here: ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "νοήσατε ἄκακοι πανουργίαν",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", \"subtlety.\" ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Ye fools, be ye of an understanding heart.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " For \"fools\" (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "khesilim",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), the intellectually heavy and dull, see on Proverbs 1:22. The heart is considered the seat of the mind or understanding (comp. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Proverbs 15:32",
        "children": []
      },
      {
